<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
COLOMBIA. Departamento Santander, Cordillera Oriental, Paramo de Almorzadero, 3500-3700 m, 20 Jun 1940, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">J. Cuatrecasas &amp; H. Garcia Barriga 9970</emphasis>
(holotype: US-1798714!; isotypes: BC-635144 seen digitally!; COL-34839 seen digitally!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
Stooling perennials forming small tussocks with intravaginal innovations. Culms 30-40 cm tall, decumbent to erect, often weak, spreading to prostrate, culm bases continuously branch and often root at low to mid-culm nodes, glabrous; nodes 2 or 3 in distal half; internodes 1.4-8.0 cm long. Leaf sheaths about 2/3 as long as the internodes, membranous, greenish-white, scabrous, upper sheaths open 1/2 the length, collars flared; ligules 1-2.5 mm long, membranous, apex acute, ephemeral; blades 5-15 cm 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.5 mm, flat, thin, lax, green, abaxially scabrous. Panicles 9-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 cm, few-flowered with 5-8 spikelets, flexuous, ovate, branched; branches glabrous. Spikelets 10-13 mm long, 4-flowered, glabrous; obovate; rachilla 1.2-2.4 mm long, minutely scabrous; glumes 1.3-3.6 mm long, membranous, lanceolate, green, glabrous, upper margins hairy; lower glumes 1.3-2 mm long, 1-nerved, apex acute; upper glumes 3-3.5 mm long, less than 
<normalizedToken originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
as long as the florets, 3-veined, apex acuminate; lemmas 6.6-8 mm long, 5-veined, lanceolate, membranous, green, scabrous, apex bifid, two-dentate, awned between the teeth, the awn 1-2 mm long; paleas 4.6-5.2 mm long, membranous, keels scabrous, apex bifid; lodicules 0.6-0.8 mm long, lanceolate; anthers 2.7-3.3 mm long; ovaries glabrous. Caryopses not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Leaf anatomy.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
The leaf anatomy of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Poa reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is C3, XyMS+ and the transverse sections have many widely spaced vascular bundles with small ribs; sclerenchyma is under both abaxial and adaxial epidermis, discontinuous, small, extending to the vascular bundles forming girders; bulliform cells are absent; epidermis is sparsely hairy. An anatomical description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Poa reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Watson, L" journalOrPublisher="C. A. B. International, Wallingford" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" refId="B38" refString="Watson, L, Dallwitz, M, 1992. The Grass Genera of the World. C.A.B. International, Wallingford" title="The Grass Genera of the World" year="1992">Watson and Dallwitz (1992)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Stancik, D" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 184" refId="B33" refString="Stancik, D, Peterson, PM, 2007. A revision of Festuca (Poaceae: Loliinae) in South American Paramos. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 56: 1 - 184" title="A revision of Festuca (Poaceae: Loliinae) in South American Paramos." volume="56" year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Stančík">Stancik</normalizedToken>
and Peterson (2007
</bibRefCitation>
, figs 13g, 77
<normalizedToken originalValue="c–f">c-f</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Flowering in July.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Poa reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the type locality, the paramo of the Colombian Cordillera Oriental, Dept. Santander (
<bibRefCitation author="Stancik, D" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 184" refId="B33" refString="Stancik, D, Peterson, PM, 2007. A revision of Festuca (Poaceae: Loliinae) in South American Paramos. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 56: 1 - 184" title="A revision of Festuca (Poaceae: Loliinae) in South American Paramos." volume="56" year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Stančík">Stancik</normalizedToken>
and Peterson 2007
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
The species is rare and its conservation status is data deficient (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="US Department of Agriculture Miscellaneous Publication" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" refId="B13" refString="IUCN, 2010. IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2010.3." title="IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2010.3" year="2010">IUCN 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
The specific epithet is probably in reference to the decumbent, spreading or prostrate culms, a frequent characteristic of the species in this subsection of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Poa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="114" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="114" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
<bibRefCitation author="Stancik, D" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 184" refId="B33" refString="Stancik, D, Peterson, PM, 2007. A revision of Festuca (Poaceae: Loliinae) in South American Paramos. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 56: 1 - 184" title="A revision of Festuca (Poaceae: Loliinae) in South American Paramos." volume="56" year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Stančík">Stancik</normalizedToken>
and Peterson (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that the spikelets and panicles of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Festuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Poa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
] 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hack. ex Sodiro" authorityName="Hack. ex Sodiro" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Aphanelytrum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aphanelytrum procumbens" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procumbens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Aphanelytrum procumbens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa hitchcockiana" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hitchcockiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Poa hitchcockiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
], but the glumes in the former are veined. They provisionally placed 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Festuca reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName authority="E.B. Alexeev" basionym-authority="(Tzvelev)" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="sect." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Glabricarpae" subGenus="Subulatae">Festuca subg. Subulatae (Tzvelev) E.B. Alexeev sect. Glabricarpae</taxonomicName>
E.B. Alexeev, as suggested by Aleexev (1986), along with 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca caldasii" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caldasii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Festuca caldasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kunth) Kunth and 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca woodii" order="Poales" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="woodii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Festuca woodii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Stančík">Stancik</normalizedToken>
. 
<pageBreakToken pageId="7" pageNumber="114" start="start">The</pageBreakToken>
latter two species of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Festuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have open sheaths, flattened and hairy (hispid?) rachillas, and lemmas with rounded keels and annulate calluses, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Poa reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has fused sheaths 
<normalizedToken originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
their length, terete rachillas that are minutely scabrous, and lemmas with compressed keels and smooth transitions from callus to lemma. We hope to confirm the placement of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa reclinata" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reclinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Poa reclinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName authority="subsect. Aphanelytrum" authorityName="subsect. Aphanelytrum (Hack.) Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="subsect. Tovarochloa (Macfarl. &amp; P. But) Soreng &amp; P. M. Peterson" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="subsect." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa" order="Poales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus" subsection="Aphanelytrum">Poa subsect. Aphanelytrum</taxonomicName>
in future DNA studies.
</paragraph>
